South African Stocks Retreat; Datatec, Lonmin, Northam Platinum Are Active

-- B y   R o b e r t   B r a n d
-- 
2011-05-09T15:48:36Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-09/south-african-stocks-retreat-datatec-lonmin-northam-platinum-are-active.html
South Africa ’s FTSE/JSE Africa All
Share Index fell 269.05, or 0.8 percent, to 31,609.78 at the 5
p.m. close in in Johannesburg.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today.  Datatec Ltd. (DTC)  , a Johannesburg-based computer
services company, fell 72 cents, or 2 percent, to 35.49 rand, a
third day of declines. Datatec expects to report earnings per
share of about 23 cents for the year through February, it said
in a regulatory filing.  FirstRand Ltd. (FSR)  , the second-largest South African
banking group, dropped 16 cents, or 0.8 percent, to 19.93 rand,
paring its increase this year to 2.2 percent. The company is
buying and taking over Finance Bank Zambia Ltd. which has 39
branches and about 1,000 workers, the Lusaka-based Post
newspaper said, citing people familiar with the industry.  Lonmin Plc (LON)  , the third-largest platinum producer,
gained 2.90 rand, or 1.7 percent, to 173.00 rand, its first
advance in eight trading sessions. Profit almost doubled in the
first half through March, rising to 45 U.S. cents a share from
23 cents a year earlier, the company said in a statement today.  Northam Platinum Ltd. (NHM)  , the operator of the world’s
deepest platinum mine, dropped 86 cents, or 1.9 percent, to
44.40 rand, taking its decrease this year to 2 percent. Northam
was downgraded to “underweight” from “neutral” at JPMorgan
Chase & Co. by equity analyst Steve Shepherd.  Sappi Ltd. (SAP)  , the world’s biggest maker of glossy
paper, dropped 1 rand, or 2.89 percent, its biggest one-day
decline since Feb. 24, after saying it expects third-quarter
earnings to be similar to earnings in the year-earlier period.  Verimark Holdings Ltd. (VMK)  , a retailer, climbed 2
cents, or 1.2 percent, to 1.64 rand after saying earnings per
share for the year ended Feb. 28 will more than double to
between 30 cents and 31.7 cents.  To contact the reporter on this story:
